The first (after Christ) is that ol the Apostles, who fulfilled their function according to His command. When Christ ceased to live on earth, there were other Apostles (as Paul and Barnabas) whose fonctions were those of Bishops. In the second place came prophets, who preached to the people, and were endowed with knowledge of the Gospel, of past testimonies and of the future. The Apostles prophesied with greater depth and vital strength and fruit than the prophets of the Old Covenant. In the third place come the Doctors, who teach the Gospel and the Prophets in public. Then comes the second hierarchy of power:¹ some have the gift of working miracles, others of healing the sick, others give help to the poor. The third hierarchy is that of the leaders of the people. They should have the discemment of spiritual gifts, in order to lead every one in the way in which he should g0; they must understand the language of those subject to them, and be able to explain God’s Word. Such are the powers by which the Church is governed, and which endure until mortal sin is committed. The highest gift bestowed on man is the grace of predestination.

Which ot' the Apostles possessed the Primacy after Christ? Peter, says Fitz-Ralph; and he gives the following reason. Peter loved Christ most, even more than John did; sor His sake, he plunged headlong into the sea. He received the primacy of rank, and is named first among the Apostles; he alone received the keys of Heaven; he was commanded to come to the Master on the waters. He alone was called to watch with our Lord; be alone drew ashore the net containing 15³ great fishes; he alone was taught by Christ how to mete out punishment; he alone was told to seed Christ's sheep and His lambs.
